  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why EM Is Needed"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Fitting a GMM means finding the parameters θ = {πk, μk, Σk} that maximise the log-likelihood of the observed data:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\ln p(\\mathbf{X} \\mid \\theta) = \\sum_{n=1}^{N} \\ln \\left( \\sum_{k=1}^{K} \\pi_k \\, \\mathcal{N}(\\mathbf{x}_n \\mid \\boldsymbol{\\mu}_k, \\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}_k) \\right)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Setting the gradient to zero gives equations that are coupled: each μk depends on the responsibilities rnk, which in turn depend on all the means and covariances simultaneously. There is no closed-form solution. The Expectation-Maximization (EM) algorithm breaks this circular dependency by iterating two steps: an E-step that computes soft assignments given current parameters, and an M-step that re-estimates parameters given those assignments."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "EM algorithm: E-step computes responsibilities, M-step updates parameters, loop until convergence"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The E-Step: Compute Responsibilities"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Given the current parameter estimates, compute the posterior probability that component k generated data point xn. This is a direct application of Bayes' rule:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "r_{nk} = \\frac{\\pi_k \\, \\mathcal{N}(\\mathbf{x}_n \\mid \\boldsymbol{\\mu}_k, \\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}_k)}{\\displaystyle\\sum_{j=1}^{K} \\pi_j \\, \\mathcal{N}(\\mathbf{x}_n \\mid \\boldsymbol{\\mu}_j, \\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}_j)}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "rnk is called the responsibility of component k for point n. It lies in [0, 1] and the responsibilities for a given point sum to 1 across all K components. A point that sits squarely inside cluster k gets rnk ≈ 1 and all others ≈ 0. A point halfway between two clusters gets roughly 0.5 for each."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The M-Step: Update Parameters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using the responsibilities as soft weights, re-estimate all parameters. First compute the effective count for each component:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "N_k = \\sum_{n=1}^{N} r_{nk}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Then update the three parameter sets:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\boldsymbol{\\mu}_k = \\frac{1}{N_k} \\sum_{n=1}^{N} r_{nk} \\, \\mathbf{x}_n"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\boldsymbol{\\Sigma}_k = \\frac{1}{N_k} \\sum_{n=1}^{N} r_{nk} \\, (\\mathbf{x}_n - \\boldsymbol{\\mu}_k)(\\mathbf{x}_n - \\boldsymbol{\\mu}_k)^\\top"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\pi_k = \\frac{N_k}{N}"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Each formula is the responsibility-weighted version of the standard mean, covariance, and fraction. When all rnk are 0 or 1 (hard assignments), these collapse to the k-means update rules."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implementation from Scratch"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import numpy as np\nfrom scipy.stats import multivariate_normal\n\n\ndef fit_gmm(X, K, n_iter=100, tol=1e-6, random_state=0):\n    \"\"\"\n    Fit a K-component full-covariance GMM via EM.\n    X: (N, D) data matrix.\n    Returns: means, covariances, weights, log_likelihoods.\n    \"\"\"\n    rng = np.random.default_rng(random_state)\n    N, D = X.shape\n\n    # --- Initialise: k-means++ style, random covariances ---\n    idx = rng.choice(N, size=K, replace=False)\n    means = X[idx].copy()                              # (K, D)\n    covs  = np.array([np.eye(D)] * K)                 # (K, D, D)\n    pis   = np.full(K, 1.0 / K)                       # (K,)\n\n    log_likelihoods = []\n\n    for iteration in range(n_iter):\n        # ---- E-step: compute responsibilities ----\n        # log_resp[n, k] = log πₖ + log N(xₙ; μₖ, Σₖ)\n        log_resp = np.zeros((N, K))\n        for k in range(K):\n            log_resp[:, k] = (\n                np.log(pis[k] + 1e-300)\n                + multivariate_normal.logpdf(X, mean=means[k], cov=covs[k])\n            )\n\n        # Log-sum-exp for numerical stability\n        log_resp_max = log_resp.max(axis=1, keepdims=True)\n        log_sum = log_resp_max + np.log(\n            np.exp(log_resp - log_resp_max).sum(axis=1, keepdims=True)\n        )\n        log_r = log_resp - log_sum          # normalised log-responsibilities\n        r     = np.exp(log_r)               # (N, K), each row sums to 1\n\n        # Track log-likelihood\n        ll = log_sum.sum()\n        log_likelihoods.append(ll)\n        if iteration > 0 and abs(ll - log_likelihoods[-2]) < tol:\n            break\n\n        # ---- M-step: update parameters ----\n        Nk = r.sum(axis=0)                  # (K,)  effective counts\n\n        for k in range(K):\n            nk = Nk[k]\n            if nk < 1e-6:                   # degenerate component — skip\n                continue\n            # Mean\n            means[k] = (r[:, k:k+1] * X).sum(axis=0) / nk\n            # Covariance\n            diff = X - means[k]             # (N, D)\n            covs[k] = (r[:, k:k+1] * diff).T @ diff / nk + 1e-6 * np.eye(D)\n            # Weight\n            pis[k] = nk / N\n\n    return means, covs, pis, log_likelihoods\n\n\n# --- Example ---\nrng = np.random.default_rng(42)\nX = np.vstack([\n    rng.multivariate_normal([0, 0], np.eye(2), 150),\n    rng.multivariate_normal([6, 6], [[2, 0.5], [0.5, 1]], 250),\n    rng.multivariate_normal([3, -3], [[1, -0.4], [-0.4, 1]], 100),\n])\n\nmeans, covs, pis, lls = fit_gmm(X, K=3, n_iter=200)\nprint(\"Converged in\", len(lls), \"iterations\")\nprint(\"Mixing weights:\", np.round(pis, 3))\n# Mixing weights: [0.3   0.5   0.2]  (ground truth: 0.3/0.5/0.2)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Convergence Guarantee"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "EM is guaranteed to be monotonically non-decreasing in log-likelihood: each E→M cycle either increases the log-likelihood or leaves it unchanged. This follows from the evidence lower bound (ELBO): the E-step tightens the bound, and the M-step maximises it. The log-likelihood is bounded above (probabilities are ≤ 1), so the sequence converges."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "However, convergence is to a local optimum, not necessarily the global one. The likelihood surface for a GMM is multimodal. Different random initialisations can lead to very different final fits. The standard remedy is to run EM multiple times with different random seeds and pick the run with the highest final log-likelihood."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture\n\n# n_init=10 runs EM 10 times and keeps the best result\ngmm = GaussianMixture(\n    n_components=3,\n    covariance_type='full',\n    n_init=10,           # multiple restarts\n    max_iter=200,\n    tol=1e-4,\n    random_state=0,\n)\ngmm.fit(X)\n\nprint(f\"Converged: {gmm.converged_}\")\nprint(f\"Final log-likelihood: {gmm.score(X) * len(X):.1f}\")\nprint(f\"Iterations used: {gmm.n_iter_}\")"
          }
        ]
      },
