      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "EM vs k-Means"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "k-means is a special case of EM with spherical, equal-variance components and hard (0/1) assignments. EM generalises this in two ways: soft assignments capture uncertainty about cluster membership, and each component can have its own arbitrary covariance structure. In return, EM is more expensive per iteration (O(NKD²) vs O(NKD) for k-means) and requires more iterations to converge."
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
